      "writtenOn": "2018-03-21T21:15:25Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Yes it works. I don\u0027t want to have to add the flags to each command. Plus we need to parse the flags before reaching each individual command because we inject a properly authenticated Machine Database RPC client into the context up front.\n\ne.g. \"crimson -service-account-json \u003cwhatever\u003e get-dcs -name dc\" works because flag.FlagSet.Parse() parses until it reaches the first non-flag (\"get-dcs\") on the command line. Everything after that gets passed to subcommands.Run (\"get-dcs\", \"-name\", \"dc\").\n\nParsing will fail on any non-auth flags that appear before the named subcommand, e.g. \"crimson -service-account-json \u003cwhatever\u003e -name dc get-dcs\" will fail because there\u0027s no -name argument to crimson, only a -name argument to get-dcs. To me that\u0027s fine because you pass high-level auth-related flags to crimson and subcommand-related flags to the subcommand.",
